[On Mon 9 May 2016, Bulgaria submitted to the OIE a report concerning 2 new LSD outbreaks, on its border with Greece; see, with map, at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=20114.
The said report does not include information on applied vaccination.

The cummulative Bulgarian LSD epidemiological statistics since the reported start of the event on 12 Apr 2016, are the following:
Total outbreaks = 17 (Submitted)
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 589 / 20 / 0 / 589 / 0

Due to the restrictive measures adopted in connection with the spread of LSD, no sheep and goat exhibitions were held during the festive 5th jubilee of the National Meeting of Sheep Breeders in Bulgaria. The remarkable event took place on 6-8 May 2016, close to the Petropavelski Monastery region, near the town of Lyaskovets. Despite the unfavourable weather conditions, more than 100 000 people attended. The different animal species were presented in alternative methods, such as a special photo exhibition (see, with picture, at http://tinyurl.com/znh92qu).

On 6 May 2016, Bulgaria's western neighbor, FYR [Former Yugoslavia Republic] Macedonia, reported 3 new outbreaks of LSD; see, with map, at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=20148.

According to a Dutch source, the entire transport of cattle from Europe to Turkey has been discontinued, since the only route passes through the infected zone in Bulgaria. Returning lorries may carry the virus (and/or infected arthropods?) back to other European countries. (see -- in Dutch -- at http://veeteelt.nl/gezondheid/nieuws/lumpy-skin-disease-rukt-verder-op-naar-noorden?device=3&device_type=0).

In Greece, LSD has resumed its spread in 2016, also in hitherto unaffected areas. The "emergency vaccination" in late 2015 was applied only in regions already affected, not preventively in neighboring and other areas. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4211194,81.]
